‚Å£
Merely using that fancy Sony with the 85mm f1.2 isn't going to magically make you a better photographer‚Å£
‚Å£
Respect the art that photographers make enough to not unnecessarily and incessantly ask them for their camera settings. Respect the art form that you've chosen to invest your time into enough to understand that it's exactly that - art‚Å£
‚Å£
The camera and settings don't make the picture. The photographer does

So, I tend to turn everything into a metaphor, it may be partly because I just tend to assume that people won't understand me if I speak the way I think, and partly because I like to seem like I've got some deep insights into the universe (which I probably don't). I love this picture. I think, more than anything else I've shot this year, and I think it's because of what it feels like. It's mundane, an everyday scene, painted in beautiful late afternoon light.

And that's what I want my life to be like, and I think I've managed that for the most part. I don't want to be someone who does amazing things and lives on a private island off the coast of Dubai or anything like that.

I want the stable peace of monotony. I just feel like lately everyone around me is trying to DO or BE something, everyone is trying to be a unicorn, and I feel like everyone around me is trying to drive me to be the same, but I just wanna be the damn grass.

I just wanted to be the sunbathed door to a Masjid, not the sixty meter wide dome at the top.

So last weekend, on Sunday evening, as the rain slowed I somehow managed to @nomaanhazarvi to join me for a photo shoot, and when we were driving to Brooklyn I observed just how weird these purple trees are

Now of course I'm probably exaggerated in my perception of them, as it's probably not *that* unusual, but I feel like they belong in a completely different world

I've been watching this series over the past week or so called Hilda, and it's an animation about this little girl with blue hair who, with her mother, moves from living in the wilderness to a city called Trolberg, the world is just beautiful in every way, from the tiny elves that are invisible unless a human signs a contract with them, to the trolls with these pointy noses that turn to balls of rock when the sun is out to the flying balls poofiness and a mad scientist whose weather predictions on the radio are suspiciously accurate

And it's odd that, I watch this series, and I just feel like these purple trees that occasionally flood our streets, would feel so at home in this quaint little world.

I buried my face deep into his dark, denim jacket. Soaked by the brisk summer drizzle flooding the earth as we rode through the city. My arms wrapped tightly around his waist, afraid, not to slip, but simply to be left behind.

The street lights flew past us, my mind awash with the streaks of reflections that chased me with every passing meter. The cold breeze mixing with the rain, harsh against my skin.

I clung tighter and tighter. Letting myself be pulled away from the torment laying in our wake.

I don't really know why I don't seem to be able to.

So, I generally keep my camera in Black and White when I'm shooting, just because it helps me to see the light a bit more clearly, and for the entire day - that was just my mental image of what I had captured.

As soon as I opened the first image this black and white picture and it turned to these bright and bold colours.

And it just shocked me to realize how the reality of things can be so vastly different to what they actually are, purely as a result of the filters that we impose on ourselves and the ways that we force our minds to see things.

I think it's rare to have your expectations shattered so quickly and completely. Maybe it should be something that happens more often.

This was Autumn, about a year and a half ago, the light was warm as it fell across the bricks. Everything was gold, the light, the ground, the buildings and the trees. Everything.

I've never seen light this beautiful since.

Did some exploring around Church Square on Sunday with Themba.

The sunset came slow, and unfortunately disappeared behind a flood of evening clouds, vanishing slowly as it dripped between the spaces.

Pretoria had an odd vibe though, young and old, old and new, all in this mishmash clumps of bricks and clay trying to be a city.

Went out to make some magic, but between the clouds that kept moving and the light that couldn't stand still, instead I took some sad pictures of a happy puppet.

There's something silently wrong here, the realization that there's so much more that goes into emotion than smiles on our faces, everything from the droop in our limbs to the invisible strings holding us back at each step. I don't think a lot of people see them, and even less realise they're there in the first place.

What's worse? Is when we make these strings our reality, because we don't know how to cut ourselves out of them. That's the tragedy of being a real boy.

There's this amazing thing about airports. Light pouring through the massive windows, giant airplanes sitting on hot tarmac in wait.

People hustling, queus spanning slow lines dripping from the open space. People flowing slowly, step by step, step by step surrounded by beeps and men on uniforms and uniforms that were supposedly attractive in the 90's.

But there's something in the humm of the plane engines starting, vibrating as the Nando's line grows longer and longer. The way each moment is stretched beyond the far and low horizon.

Have you ever been in that state where you're sleeping but your mind is still so awake, like when you're really tired or just as your morning alarm sets in? In that state where you're starting to fall into or out of consciousness

Have you ever just listened to the earth then, felt the rhythm of it? The beat behind the birds and the cars, the whistling in the wind and soft falling rain

Have you ever fallen into it? The pace of the world, becoming one with your surroundings. Your heartbeat falling into its pace, as your mind sinks into a quiet bliss

Because if you have, you'd know, that's where peace resides, not in changing what's around you, but rather in letting things fall into where they must be
